\series bold 
Introduction
\series default 
 
\layout Standard

In this exercise you will investigate a series LRC circuit through measurements
 of the voltage across the generator, the resistor, the capacitor, and the
 inductor in the circuit.
 The computer will be used as a storage oscilloscope to make these measurements
 and to illustrate the phase relationships among the voltages across the
 circuit elements.
\layout Standard

Consider the series LRC circuit shown in the figure below with a generator
 of voltage amplitude V, a resistor R, a capacitor C, and an inductor having
 inductance L and resistance r.
 Note that the capacitor is assumed to have no resistance.
 Also shown in the figure is the phasor diagram for the voltages V, V
\begin_inset Formula \( _{R} \)
\end_inset 

, V
\begin_inset Formula \( _{C} \)
\end_inset 

, V
\begin_inset Formula \( _{L} \)
\end_inset 

, and V
\begin_inset Formula \( _{r} \)
\end_inset 

.
 From the phasor diagram, we can write the following expressions:
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V=\sqrt{(V_{L}-V_{C})^{2}+(V_{R}+V_{r})^{2}}\]

\end_inset 


\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tan \phi =\frac{V_{L}-V_{C}}{V_{R}+V_{r}}\]

\end_inset 


\layout Standard
